 also because this image dominated cognitive maps of the oceanic world.As the first study of coastlines and early modern English literature, Dire Straits investigates the tensions of the classical tradition’s isolation of the British Isles from the domain of poetry. By illustrating how early modern English writers created their works in the context of a longstanding cultural inheritance from antiquity, Elizabeth Jane Bellamy offers a new approach to the history of early modern cartography and its influences on literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCartography in literature. 0aCoasts in literature. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLandscapes in literature. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269424840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442694248423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442694248.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK